temporaries, included the use of the alphabet, the teaching of texts in schools, the public inscription of laws, the sending and receiving of letters, the exchange of city coinage, and the making of lists. Having changed the way cultural material was processed and transmitted, the technology of writing also led to innovations in the way stories were told, and Wise contends that theatre was the result. However, the art of drama appeared in ancient Greece not only as a beneficiary of literacy but also in defiance of any tendency to see textuality as an end in itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGreek dramaxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aInvention (Rhetoric)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiteracyzGreecexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLiterary formxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTheaterzGreecexHistoryyTo 500. 0aWritten communicationzGreecexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150174494540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501744945423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501744945/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK